function findCenter(edges) {
    if (edges[0][0] === edges[1][0] || edges[0][0] === edges[1][1]) {
        return edges[0][0];
    }
    return edges[0][1];
}
```

    The algorithm only needs to examine the first two elements in the edges array because it knows that the graph is a star graph. In such a graph, every node is connected to the center node. So, the center node must appear twice in the first two elements of the edges array (once in each edge). The algorithm checks if the first node in the first edge is the center by seeing if it exists in the second edge. If it does not, the function returns the second node in the first edge, as that must be the center. This approach has a constant time complexity (O(1)) because it examines a fixed number of array elements, regardless of the size of the input matrix.

